      "side": 1,
      "message": "Just to add to this discussion - This behavior was taken from patch https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/vpp/+/45167, after offline discussion with Jerome.\n\nIf the interrupt is set immediately in case of 0 timeout, that we would set the interrupt for the sfdp-expire node every time `sfdp_session_timer_update` is called with `timeout_seconds`/`ticks` \u003d\u003d 0.\n\nThis is fine for test scenarios, but IMO it can be problematic in scenarios where we force session expiry quite frequently (i.e. in SFDP tcp-check service, with l4-lifecycle enabled \u0026 when a TCP session completes). At worst case, that would mean we would set the interrupt / call sfdp-expire for every vector containing at least one packet triggering a session expiry.",
      "parentUuid": "57e0c2fc_5dbafcb6",
      "revId": "895d2c952d952164e7f7bf63786fd37acc8f99ec",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "25c73ea2_47c83458",
        "filename": "src/vnet/sfdp/timer/timer.h",
        "patchSetId": 19
      },
      "lineNbr": 128,
      "author": {
        "id": 333
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-01T16:47:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Following Hadi\u0027s comment, this behavior was intentionally removed in PS23. Setting an interrupt on every ticks \u003d\u003d 0 in sfdp_session_timer_update would trigger one interrupt per session expiry in production (e.g. every TCP teardown with l4-lifecycle enabled), which is too expensive. The immediate interrupt is now only in sfdp_expire_session_now, where it is explicitly needed.",
      "parentUuid": "c5bb7e92_5d3cc7f3",
      "revId": "895d2c952d952164e7f7bf63786fd37acc8f99ec",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
